@node Introduction "VirusZ Check File 2 v2.10 - Introduction"
@next Requirements
@prev TOC
@help HelpPage
@font XEN.font 11

@{b}Introduction:@{ub}

Welcome to CheckFile2 for people who wish to check files (archives AND/OR regular files!) for viruses (virii) @{b}easily@{ub}. It was made specifically to be run from your @{" favourite program " link Installation} (ala DOpus 4 and others) or even via menu programs.  It checks inside the archives LZX, LHA, LZH, DMS, ZIP & RAR archives.  If it isn't one of those compacted formats it checks the file by itself for viruses.

The Program has been tested throughly on over 2 Gigabytes of archives and hundreds of Megabytes of files upon my system.  To date I have not encountered any problems.  (Otherwise it would not have been publically released..  :)

Although the new version of VirusZ contains checking theis program offers easier setup then the one contained in VirusZ v1.33+ itself.  Also this can be altered to work with BBS software and directory utilities easily.

I have tested the program on various virus infected archives and files and the script notifies you of the viruses!  (The whole purpose of it all!)

It has taken @{" -*much*- of my time " link History} to make this program as smooth running and intelligent as possible to handle @{" everyday life situations " link Installation} you may face.

If you wish any changes or improvements to the program please do not hesitate to request the alteration(s) from @{" Paul (The author) " link Contact}.

-=>  Many thanks goto the Author of VirusZ  (Georg Hörmann)  <=-

Thanks to:
Term!nator (BBS Addz),
Blade (Laughs in chat),
Seona (Looking good, Good humour, etc.. ;)


@endnode
@node Requirements "VirusZ Check File 2 v2.10 - Requirements"
@next Purpose
@prev Introduction
@help HelpPage
@font XEN.font 11

@{b}Requirements:@{ub}


What you need for this program to operate fully:

@{fg highlight}-@{fg text}  VirusZ v1.3x+  (Available on AmiNET)

@{fg highlight}-@{fg text}  LZX, LHA, DMS, UnZip & UnRar in your path (IE. C: dir) (Available on AmiNET)

@{fg highlight}-@{fg text}  RexxMaster Running  (Part of Workbench 2+)



Suggested extras:

@{fg highlight}-@{fg text}  A virtual disk of some sort.  (IE. fms.device or statram.device)

@{fg highlight}-@{fg text}  020+ for faster checking.

@{fg highlight}-@{fg text}  An old Public Enemy album to listen to. :)



@endnode
@node Purpose "VirusZ Check File 2 v2.10 - Purpose"
@prev Requirements
@next Installation
@help HelpPage
@font XEN.font 11

@{b}Purpose:@{ub}

This program is specifically to work in conjunction with VirusZ to search inside archives for viruses quickly and easily without breaking into a sweat as the present VirusZ is like to setup.  I started to program this after near enough every program such as VirusChecker, Xtruder and some others required yourself to register to check inside archives.

As I recently took over a BBS and wanted a certain amount of security for users and I started to check all new archives/files coming in with a virus checker.  After some time I realised the slow method of DeArchiving and virus checking each and every archive which required a lot of swapping screens and programs all the time.  Needless it was slow and TERRIBLY boring.

I then saw CheckArc.vzrx for VirusZ which knows a decent amount of viruses and noticed it missed a few compacters that existed that are in regular use.  There started my adventure in ARexx programming.  Myself being a beginner with basic knowledge in programming from school and computer use for over 14 years I improved the checker extensively leading to what you have here now which checks archives and files EASILY by the user.

My program was used extensively used on all my BBS archives and was adapted even for other purposes later (Updating BBS adds in Arcs (900meg+ in one hit).. :).

The program in essence is devoted to Free virus checker programs.
This is another reason why I chose VirusZ.
Firstly it is Free.
Secondly it is better in Virus Recognition then Xtruder!
The question is why these guys don't have Internet accounts for myself to pass on viruses?!

May the authors of the virus checkers move ahead and at least get a Internet EMail address.
(It costs $10 (Australian! [$about $8 US]) here in Australia on a local Amiga* BBS!!)


Amiga* is a tradmark of <Insert forever changing company owner here> International.
@endnode
@node Installation "VirusZ Check File 2 v2.10 - Installation"
@prev Purpose
@next ToDo
@help HelpPage
@font XEN.font 11

@{b}Installation:@{ub}

For installation upon your system it is a good idea to use a file management program.  Personally I know a lot of Directory Opus 4 users and use it myself at times..  (Closer to 'live out of'.. :)

I suggest that users check inside the AREXX script to see if the settings are truely correct for their system.  The ones in question are:

@{b}VirusZ_prg = "@{ub}<Path and what filename VirusZ is>@{b}"@{ub}

examples might be..

@{b}VirusZ_prg = "@{ub}SYS:Virus/VirusZ@{b}"@{ub}
or could be..
@{b}VirusZ_prg = "@{ub}SYS:Utilities/VirusZ/VirusZ@{b}"@{ub}


The @{b}LHA_prg, LZX_prg, ZIP_prg, RAR_prg, DMS_prg@{ub} settings can be changed easily.  If they are in your path, IE C: dir or somehwere that the path is specified before you hit WB then there is no need to change em otherwise list the path that exist in.

The setting @{b}DirPath = "@{ub}RAM:T/TempArcDir@{b}"@{ub}  can be changed to a real device to put the unarchives file to be checked if you have limited Ram.  This could be "SYS:T/TempArcDir".  The directory will be created and deleted afterwards and no need to worry about other files in that dir as they will be unaltered.

The setting '@{b}DiskTemp@{ub}' is for what device you wish to check DMS archives on.  It can be either a DFx: device or alternatively a virtual device.  Namely something like VFx: (fms.)devices or Statram deiveces configured properly.

The setting '@{b}DiskBlnk@{ub}' will format the drive that was used to check the DMS archive.  This is so virus infected disks will not be run accidently afterwards or free memory on statram devices.

The setting '@{b}FormatName@{ub}' is the name of the disk once blanked if you have the DiskBlnk option YES.

The setting '@{b}DiskRmve@{ub}' is used to UnMount a volume after the checking occurs.  This is useful if you wih to use a device such as RAD to check one disk and remove it afterwards afterwards so you dont have RAD sitting around after your checking happens.

The setting '@{b}Remove_prg@{ub}' is the program used to Dismount the virtual floppy you use.


For running it is possible to set the switch "@{b}QUIT@{ub}" which will quit VirusZ after each file checked.  This is for people with limited ram which do not need VirusZ running all the time.  It is shown up in each program setup as [QUIT] Meaning that it is optional upon how you want it running after your Virus Check.

Please note that you can only notify VirusZ Check File 2 to check one(1) file each time it is run.


       For best performance, set it up this way in a button / menu:


@{fg highlight}@{u}For Directory Opus 4 (© 1993 Jonathan Potter) Setup:@{uu}@{fg text}

             @{b}AmigaDOS@{ub}    Rx REXX:CheckFile2.vzrx {o} [QUIT]

                             Stack size: 4096
                                Priority: 0
                              Close delay: -1


                           @{b}Switches to turn on:@{ub}

                                 CD source
                               Do all files
                               Output window
                           Recursive directories
                             Reload each file



@{fg highlight}@{u}For DirWork (© 1990-1994 Chris Hames) Setup:@{uu}@{fg text}
(Not sure if previous versions work the in the same manner)


             @{b}Program@{ub}     Rx REXX:CheckFile2.vzrx %p%f [QUIT]


                            @{b}Switches to turn on:@{ub}

                        Close window after each one


                          @{b}Cycle Gadgets Settings:@{ub}

                            CD source directory
                              Selected Files


                             @{b}Misc to turn on:@{ub}
                              Current Source
                               No Requester



@{fg highlight}@{u}For AmigaShell Use:@{uu}@{fg text}

Type:

Rx REXX:REXX:CheckFile2.vzrx <Filename> [QUIT]


You can also set it up as an alias in Shell-Startup.  This will allow you to type one name for the program and then the file/archive to check.  This saves you a lot of typing needless to say.  To set it up put the following line in your Shell-Startup:

alias Check Rx REXX:FileChecker2.vzrx


To make this alias working you can either close all Shells and restart Shell and the new alias will also be loaded from Shell Startup.

To check a file/archive for example by using this new alias and the archive is called "CheckMe.LZX" you would type at a DOS prompt:
(Making sure that you are CDed to the directory the file resides)

Check CheckMe.LZX


That would check the file "CheckMe.LZX" for any viruses.




@{b}@{u}Installation Procedure:@{uu}@{ub}

If you wish to install the program upon your system disk (Harddisk or floppy) just press the the next line.  Then set it up according to above information.

@{b}To install Press:  @{" INSTALL File Check 2 " system "NewShell Window=CON:0/50//100/VirusZ Check File 2 Installer Window!/Auto/Close from CheckFile2_Install"}@{ub}.

(For Manual setup just copy the script to your REXX: directory/assign)

@endnode
